Description: McKesson Corp. agreed to settle allegations that it violated federal reporting provisions relating to its handling of certain prescription medications regulated by the Drug Enforcement Administration.  Under the agreement between the company and six U.S. Attorney's Offices, McKesson agreed to pay $13,250,000 in civil penalties for alleged violations of its obligations under the Controlled Substances Act.

McKesson Corporation, a wholesale pharmaceutical distributor, agreed to pay the United States $3 million to settle claims that it overcharged the Department of Defense from October 1997 to December 2001.

Description: McKesson Corporation agreed to pay the United States more than $190 million to resolve claims that it violated the False Claims Act by reporting inflated pricing information for a large number of prescription drugs.

McKesson Corporation, a large distributor of pharmaceutical drugs, agreed to pay a $150 million civil penalty for alleged violations of the Controlled Substances Act relating to the failure to report suspicious orders of products such as oxycodone and hydrocodone.

McKesson Corporation agreed to pay $18 million to resolve allegations that it improperly set temperature monitors used in shipping vaccines under its contract with the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.

Description: The verdict in this gender discrimination case was upheld by the Seventh Circuit Court of Appeals in ruling No. 04-3816.

Private Litigation Case Title: Chang, et al v. McKesson HBOC, Inc., et al

Agency: Labor Department Wage and Hour Division

Description: McKesson Corp. agreed to pay $15 million in settlement of allegations it conspired to inflate the average wholesale prices of drugs it distributed, resulting in greater costs for Medicaid.
McKesson Corp agreed to pay $9.84 million in settlement of alleged improper reporting of the average wholesale price of its drugs, causing Medicaid to overpay.

McKesson, one of the largest drug wholesalers, agreed to pay $151 million to settle multistate litigation alleging that the company inflated the price of prescription drugs by as much as 25 percent, causing the states' Medicaid programs to overpay millions of dollars in pharmacy reimbursements. This was separate from a $190 million settlement the company reached with the federal government on the same issue; see the Violation Tracker entry at https://violationtracker.goodjobsfirst.org/violation-tracker/-mckesson-corporation-0
settlement of allegations that McKesson inflated the price of drugs prescribed for beneficiaries of two Ohio public pension funds and the state's workers compensation system.
McKesson agreed to pay $37 million to settle allegations that it violated the Virginia Fraud Against Taxpayers Act by conspiring to inflate prices for more than 400 brand-named prescription drugs.
inflating reported drug prices

Drug distributor McKesson agreed to pay $37 million to settle state allegations that it failed to appropriately monitor the distribution of painkillers to pharmacies, exacerbating the opioid epidemic in West Virginia.

Description: The three major pharmaceutical distributors--McKesson, AmerisourceBergen and Cardinal Health--reached a $21 billion settlement with a group of states to resolve litigation alleging the improper sale of pain medications, contributing to the national opioid epidemic.
